segments.text: Let me go back to those statements again.
Dean Kyle, I worked with him after that.
He not only was Ambassador to Guatemala after he retired there, but he served on the Farm Credit Board in Houston, and I served on the board there during the 50s.
So we learned to know each other, and I always had the highest respect for him.
I believe Kyle Field was named for Dean Kyle.
He was chairman of the Athletic Committee.
But an incidentalist nephew, Sid Kyle, was one of the star basketball players that lately made a big contribution to A&M.
But anyway, there's fine, fine.
The other is Dr. Bridges P. Lee, back in this statement, that remember people are important.
I learned that so much.
my later life being a county agent, working with people in the cooperation.
But Dr. Virgil Lee went down there and headed up Production Credit Corporation in Houston.
I believe he's still living.
He's retired.
Very active and high up in rosary clubs and things like that.
But those are the two men, the statements I can remember the best.
But there's others, mind you.
They were just so good.
In fact, I don't remember having any teacher down there that I didn't have the highest regard for, and I did get something from them.
A couple of people I've talked to had had some problems with the chemistry department.
Well, I didn't.
In fact, I'd taken chemistry in high school, and I liked chemistry.
So to me, it was not a bad course, Tom.
Well, they didn't say that they didn't like the people.
It's just it was a hard course to pass.
Well, to me, it was easy.
And I know each one has pumped out a lot.
What attitudes did the students have towards the administration, that is, both the academic administration of the president and the military administration of the bull?
I think it was very, very good.
In fact, I can't keep from thinking, the first president when I was there, Dr. Bazell, when I was there incidentally about my junior year, went to Oklahoma University.
But I've always considered him as one of the outstanding presidents.
He had the, well, just everything it would take to be an outstanding president.
Then Dr. Walton had followed.
He came up through the Extension Service.
was good.
And, of course, the commander, what did we call him?
Generally, I believe they called him the Bull.
Commandant.
Commandant.
Well, to my knowledge, we didn't have any trouble when I was there.
That reminds me of a story you want me to tell you?
Sure.
Well, about the commandant, military.
In my senior year, it was Austin Hall there.
Me and my
roommate, Earl McCoy, the captain.
We roomed on the second floor.
One morning began to be a lot of liquid come down through the ceiling.
So we got as scared as everything.
And it turned out that somebody was making a home brew up there.
Well, so had me.
And I know the captain of the company, Earl McCoy, didn't know anything about it.
But he got that cleaned up and cleaned out up there pretty quickly.
And to my knowledge, he combed that and everything.
And we would have inspectors come through the dormitory pretty often.
That's the nearest we had to booze or whiskey in my four years at A&M was that up there.
And I didn't even know it was there.
And we didn't have the picture.
or a pound down there to catch it.
That took some pretty enterprising students.
Yes, it did.
To make up a batch of homebrew, and I imagine you had a fairly frequent inspection of your rooms, didn't you?
We did, an inspection of the room.
That's one thing the cadet corps taught you.
Make up your bed, keep your shoes shined, and keep your room orderly and all.
And you know, as old as I am, and my wife will take care of all these years, and then this and that will be made,
I still like the idea of when a person gets up making up his bed, mind you, don't do it.
Well, in my four years of college, even though it was not a military school, that was a common practice of both my roommate and I.
We made up our beds when we got up.
One of the things that I think is of interest about Texas A&M is the number of traditions which have been going on, such things as the bonfire, the senior boots, and things of that nature.
Can you remember any things of this nature that were started while you were there?
No.
The bonfire was going on when I was there.
Of course, it's a fresh one.
And as upperclassmen, we got out and got the poles, timber, and so forth to make.
We enjoyed that.
Another thing we enjoyed was yell practice.
We would do it then up in front of the Y.
We'd get out there every so many evenings a week and have yell practice, particularly during the football season, some basketball.
But those things, I don't recall offhand without thinking,
any tradition that was started or something new that was started when I was there.

One thing that I think, one thing I've observed in the three years I've been there is the week before the SMU game all the fish have to make spurs and make them out of coat hangers and coke bottle tops.
Did the fish have to make the spurs while you were there?
No, in my time we didn't.
You didn't do that.
Well, let's see, I believe, what, the senior boots started about the time you were there, didn't they?
Senior boots was on when I was there.
They were already wearing them.
You could wear boots if you could afford them, or you could wear leather leggings.
There were one or two of them.
But only seniors could wear the leather leggings?
Yes, that's right.
The other students wore what?
They wore your wrap leggings.
Uh-huh.
Just wrap you around.
Let me tell you a story on that, you know.
Every other year, we would go to Austin for the Texas game.
So we'd go over the train, walk up Congress Avenue, which is uphill.
So we'd get off and on.
We'd have our guns.
We'd walk and on, keep a step.
There's probably a little strain.
our legs would swell.
Those leggings, you know, they really were tight when we got up there at the Capitol building.
I'll never forget that.
You just couldn't hardly walk.
They kind of cut off the circulation when your legs would begin to swell, wouldn't they?
Did you have a muster any of the time that you were there?
I mean, we know that they started a muster of some sort in April 21st in 1903, but... You know, if we did, I don't remember.
Recently, I tinned the last muster down there, but to my knowledge, that's the only muster I ever tinned unless, of course, we had it out there in front of the wire or something like that.
Mm-hmm.
But I don't recall it.
It could have, but I forget.
I'm sure the death that started in 1903, I'm sure we had no time there.
But I just don't happen to recall.
I know I didn't take an active part in it, other than be present.
I was always present.
If I lost a milking cow, I was present.
You mentioned earlier that you ate your breakfast fairly near the table that the athletes had for their meals.
Were there any other privileges that the athletes enjoyed?
No, not that I know of.
At that time, I don't recall them being in a separate dormitory.
If they were, I don't remember.
I don't know what hall it was or what not, but I do know
But for breakfast, they would have a special table over there and would have their breakfast served to them there in the kitchen, side of the kitchen.
But I don't remember the athletes having it.
Frankly, I don't even remember if they having scholarships.
They could have.
I wouldn't have known anything.
So they had to attend the regular drills?
They may have been excused from some of them.
I expect they were.
Probably if they were practicing football at the same time as drills.
Yes, I'm sure they've been excused.
Were there ever any girls in any of the classes you attended?
No, sirree.
There was no girls on that campus.
When the girls came there, it was on a special occasion.
That time, TWU, Texas Women's University of Denton, they'd come down for football games or special occasions or something like that.
But to my knowledge, they was not a girl, they was not a lady, even a wife of a student.
We had a few students who were not in the cadet corps, living off the campus proper, so to speak.
But I never saw a girl in an A&M class until I went back there a few months ago and attended the classes down there of Dr. Snyder's on cooperation.
And we had one girl in one of the classes.
Well, I have indications that there were occasionally girls attending classes during the regular sessions.
Not in my time, but I sure never saw one on the campus except for the Space Academy.
I think during summer they could attend pretty regularly.
They might do it.
I never did go to summer school.
Well, there were no military activities on in the summers, I think, but there was some of that.
I worked every summer, yeah.
had an indication in looking at your senior yearbook that you were a distinguished student in 1924.
What did one have to do to be a distinguished student?
I don't, frankly I'd forgotten that, but I'm sure it was because my grades were high.
Well, you were also a member of the Panhandle Club, which was a regional club.
That was.
But you were also the Creaming Cow Club.
That was the dairy club.
That was called the Creaming Cow.
All the people who majored in dairy husbandry were eligible for that.
Did that meet monthly, or do you recall?
Well, frankly, I don't recall, but I doubt they met monthly.
Probably on call mostly, but could have met monthly.
I frankly have just forgotten, but I do remember being a member of it.
At one point you were president, starting with the yearbook.
Yes.
Okay, and being on, you were twice on the dairy judging team as a junior and then on the national dairy husbandry judging team.
How were the members of those teams selected?
They were selected, you'd get out there and judge cattle, judge deer cattle, place them, you know, and the ones that placed them the highest, I mean the most correct, was on the team.
I guess I had some very good meetings, I have to tell you a story on that.
You don't mind a little comedy, do you?
No, not at all.
Well, I'll never forget, we were staying at the La Salle Hotel in Chicago.
There, Professor Darnell was there, coach, teacher.
Well, we wanted to go to a show right close there, you know.
I guess you'd call it a girly show now.
But anyway, we sort of looked around the hotel for Dr.
Professor Darnell.
We couldn't see him.
So we got over there, you know, sitting about the middle, looked right down in the front seat, and there was Dr. Darnell.
So we never did let him know we were there.
Well, I have an acquaintance who told a story something similar to that in a very recent year about having gone to a
to another kind of national meeting and going to a show similar to that.
And they were all the professors from his department at the same time.
So I guess the faculty hadn't changed that much.
No, they hadn't.
Back to this selection of the team, did say the faculty in dairy husbandry first judge the dairy cattle to see how they would place them?
And then the students who came closest to that?
I'd say the coach judged them.
The coach judged them first.
He judged them, and if you placed them like he placed them, well, you were right.
And then when you went to a show, they had judges, I would say.
And would they then judge them first, and then the team that placed them closest to that would be the winning team?
As a team and as individuals.
So a team could have the top individual but not come out too well in the standings of the team.
That's possible.
You graduated then in the spring of 1927.
Did you have a job?
It all lightened up by the time you graduated?
Yes, I did.
I came out to Seminole in Gaines County before I graduated.
They promised me or they gave me a job as county agent in Gaines County.
So I was county agent in Gaines County starting in 27, then about 28.
or 29, they added Terry County to it.
Then they separated the two and I preferred to stay in Terry County because they had more farmers and they had more kids.
I was great on the 4-H club kids.
We still had those country school hours and we had a 4-H club in every country school.
Both boys and girls was in it.
We didn't have a home demonstration agent in either of those counties.
So I was there, and then I went to Plainview in 32 as county agent up there, and they did have a home demonstration agent there.
So as county agent, was it primarily your function to work with the 4-H club?
Yes, it was, and with the farmers.
With the farmers.
Did you do somewhat similar to the county agent's job today, distribute bulletins?
Somewhat, except we had much fewer bulletins then.
We had much fewer.
Oh, specialist.
County agent was county agent then.
And we looked at A&M, and we would have what we called a short course, I believe we called it down there in the summer.
Terry County would generally have more down there.
We'd drive to post and catch a train down there and go there.
And you know, some of my...
One of them became a state senator in New Mexico.
Another, very good past, became a millionaire in the grain business.
So it's very interesting, very good.
But that's where I go back to Dr. Lee's statement.
People is the most important thing.
So then how long were you county agent there?
Five years.
In Plainview?
Plainview, I left, went up to Plainview in September of 30 and went with the Hale County Deer Association in February of 32.
From then on, I've been with cooperatives.
What cooperatives have you been with?

I was with the Hale County Deer Association, which became the Plains Cooperative of Kringman, 32 to 38, and went with the Houston Bank Cooperative as secretary and vice president from 38 to 43, and came out here as general manager of the mill out here from 43 to 71.
The Hales County Dairy Association would be an organization of dairy farmers.
Dairy farmers.
In those days, every farmer milked cow and sold cream or milk for cheese making.
We became the largest creamer making butter and cheese in several southwestern states.
So the farmers, instead of selling the cream to a commercial creamery, established their own creamery.
That's right.
And they could produce it.
They could make more money.
Make more money.
We'd pay dividends.
And then you would also buy yourwould the farmers then buy their feed through the cooperative?
At that time, we didn't have a feed cooperative like they have now.
They would buy their gasoline and oil from what we call a consumer station just across the street from Cramer.
But I would suppose at that point most of the dairy farmers raised a good bit of their own feed, wouldn't they?
They raised most of their own feed and had pastures.
But they did buy some feed, but we had no cooperative dairy feed like we have now.
The Farm Credit Association in Houston, what was the function of that organization?
Well, it started with the Federal Land Bank in 1917 making loans up to twenty years on farm land.
Then, about 1923, they added what they called the Intermediate Credit Bank that would make loans for short-term loans for production for ranchers and farmers.
Then about 1934, they had the Cooperative Bank and Production Credit Association, which was financed out of the Federal Intermediate Credit Bank.
But they had what they called the Production Credit Corp. place, which Dr. Lee headed up.
But I would say, without a doubt, in my opinion,
The farm credit system is the greatest system that's ever been developed in Washington for the farmer.
Because in it, thank goodness, they required the farmer to buy stock, 5% stock, out of each dollar loan.
So pretty soon, in 53, and incidentally, I was very active in getting that through to work.
we could remove it from the Department of Agriculture and make it an independent government agency where the borrowers paid all the expenses.
And in doing so, they elected all the directors and operate the system themselves.
Now, it's totally on.
Their bonds that they sell are not guaranteed by the government at all.
So I'd say it's been one of the greatest examples
of the government helping the people to help themselves.
And then you became general manager of the Plains Co-op oil mill.
In 1943, and it was broke, just like the Hill County Deer Association was broke.
I went with that creamery plain deal, $100 a month less than I was getting this county agent.
But I liked to work.
I liked to think of it.
And so we got things straightened out.
They came out here while the stock was worth six cents on the dollar.
They grew in the largest oil, cotton seed oil mill in the world.
Working with people.
So this is the, the, the foreign cotton growers then bring their cotton seed to the mill.
Well really, the cotton growers own the cooperative gin.
They bring their cotton.
Seed cotton to the gin is gin.
The gin buys the seed, and the gin was a member of the mill.
So the mill was a federation of cooperative gin.
It started in 1937, but had some bad years, like what broke.
I gather from what I've been able to pick up that that was not an uncommon thing for cooperatives to go broke at it.
Well, that was true.
They were underfinanced.
Well, I'll tell you a little story.
Now, Hill County Deer Association, when it started, they couldn't borrow from the banks up there.
They borrowed from the Plainview Savable Loan Association and agreed to pay them 12.5% interest.
This was 1927.
Well, when the Depression hit, the Plainview Savable Loan Association went broke.
So instead of getting 2.5% of that money back, which they're supposed to get, they got nothing back.
So we were paying 12.5% interest up there in depression.
And we refinanced, and I make this claim, that I paid the highest interest that any cooperator's ever paid, and I paid the lowest.
And we refinanced them.
The old federal board, you know, under President Hoover,
I hit the low market one-eighth of one percent, one-hundredth of what we were paying.
So you refinanced your note and then paid it off after that?
That's right.
Then when we expanded, of course, we borrowed from the Houston Bank and cooperated.
We paid about four percent there.
So the plains mill was in pretty sad shape when you came to it?
Well, it was just on the bottom.
And you saw it?
I thoughtI was working with the bank and calling on them, and my two boys were growing up, our two boys were growing up, so Dennis and me were both raised out here in Miradace Middle.
So we wanted to come back to Plains.
They gave me a chance at it.
So I came back out here and took it.
And I've never regretted it because we had some dry years, but right after World War
began to develop irrigation out here, and the mill began to get more seed, and quickly grew into the biggest oil mill in the world.
Okay, so I'll ask this largely out of my own ignorance.
What is the oil used for?
The oil is used as human food.
Cotton seed oil competes with other vegetable oils, including lard, animal fat.
But cotton seed oil has a few qualities.
It's the best solid oil there is.
And as such, it bring a little primal soybean oil, which is the big vegetable oil, because it's so much bigger than cottonseed.
But cottonseed oil is used, of course, the protein, the meal, is used as animal feed, you know.
They're trying to make it into a food now.
That is, once you've crushed the seed and extracted the oil, the solid matter that's left is made into feed.
They're the meal.
The first you get off of is the letters.
Then you have the hose.
Then you have your meal.
Then you have your oil.
It's about, I don't know, really about five products.
First and second cut letters, hose, and meal, and oil.
So there's not any of it that's wasted.
No, sir.
No, sir.
And you know, A&M contributed a lot to that.
Mr. A.L.
Ward, before my time down there, just a few years ago,
He proved that cotton seed meal was good cattle and sheep feed.
It had been killing hogs and chickens, but for ruminants and all, cattle and sheep, it was good.
So I would credit that to the research station there at Texas A&M and A.O.
Washington.
Well, you say they're now doing a good bit of research there on making human feed out of the cotton seed.
Move it up the ladder.
At first it was fertilizer, and then it was feed.
Now it's going to be food.
Since you've retired from the Plains Cooperative Mill, you've been associated with the Textile Research Center at Texas Tech?
Yes.
Or were you associated with that before retirement?
After retirement.
Enjoyed it through, and I think we got some things started out there.
It's going to be as revolutionary as this cotton seed mill.
What sort of projects are you doing out there?
Well, what we were doing out there, I think the one that we were doing everything out there that Texter Mill wanted to do, but the one that really broke through was on what we call open-end spinning.
It would handle our low-grade cotton and low-micronaire cotton
make a good yarn, and in turn make a good fabric, coarse fabric, like denim, twilled, and things like that.
Well, I suppose we need a lot more denim with the popularity of blue jeans.
I believe it's here to stay.
I believe so, too.
So then it makes the low-grade cotton a more profitable commodity.
It has been a discount cotton.
It's going to raise the value.
which will raise the whole economy of the Plains area.
And we're getting textile mills out here, too.
I've spent all my time on that.
You're what, trying to encourage textile mills?
Textile mills to come out here.
Both foreign and domestic.
You had much success so far?
Yes, so far we have.
We've got a combination here of what we call Feather Fabrics, a local cap planer.
hauling mill called Hinkedi.
Then we have the Japanese people coming in to Leveland, which will be called Diwaba, America.
And then we have two small textile mills here, one at Abernathy, one at Loringa, which are trying to change over to open and spinning.
And frankly, the cooperators are trying to work out a program here where they can go all the way and produce the fabric out here of denim.
And that's still in the development stage.
But it's coming along.
So that in addition to improving a lot of the cotton producer, you will also be creating additional jobs for... Additional jobs.
You know, I served as chairman of the Protection of Rural Development Commission.
You can look at the record.
We had an out-migration of 10 to 25 percent during the 60s of our population.
was far and beyond larger, more mechanized, more chemicals.
Didn't need people.
Some people left.
And now we're trying to develop agri-industries.
And Texas will offer us one of our great opportunities.
